# Authenticate users with GOV.UK One Login

To issue credentials, your service must use GOV.UK One Login to authenticate users. This makes sure credentials are issued into a wallet that is logged in as the same user the credential is for.

When you register your service with GOV.UK One Login, you receive a unique client identifier. You must include this as a `clientId` claim in the pre-authorised code your service generates as part of issuing a credential offer. See [generate a credential offer](/issue-a-credential/credential-offer).

You must also request that the GOV.UK One Login onboarding team activates the `walletSubjectId` custom claim for your client. This claim is not enabled by default. Without it, your service cannot perform the rightful holder check required to issue a credential.

When your user authenticates with GOV.UK One Login, you obtain their user information, which includes their GOV.UK Wallet subject identifier (`walletSubjectId`). This is a pairwise identifier you use to confirm that the user who authenticated with your service is the same user who has the wallet you are issuing the credential to.
